500|$|The 1990s saw {{the onset}} of {{diametric}} changes in official Mexican government policies towards indigenous and linguistic rights. Developments of accords in the international rights arena combined with domestic pressures (such as social and political agitation by the Zapatista Army of National Liberation and indigenous social movements) led to legislative reforms {{and the creation of}} decentralized government agencies like National Commission for the Development of Indigenous Peoples (CDI) and Instituto Nacional de Lenguas Indígenas (INALI) with responsibilities for the promotion and protection of indigenous communities and languages. In particular, the federal Ley General de Derechos Lingüísticos de los Pueblos Indígenas [...] recognizes all the country's indigenous languages, including Nahuatl, as [...] "national languages" [...] and gives indigenous people the right to use them in all spheres of public and private life. In Article 11, it grants access to compulsory, bilingual and <b>intercultural</b> <b>education.</b> Nonetheless, progress towards institutionalizing Nahuatl and securing linguistic rights for its speakers has been slow.|$|E
